Haenyeo: Women of the Sea.

In South Korea, the scariest thing people have fear of is not Kim Jongun, but ahjumma (old women). They are the strongest and bossiest people you may ever encounter while having a trip to Korea, although they can also be very sweet and motherly. But I‚Äòm here to talk about a particular kind of Korean women, which is Jeju‚Äôs haenyeo, translated as sea women. Jeju is a South Korean island, a majestic place full of flourishing nature and breathtaking landscapes. Last year, along the way, me and @eleluche met many ahjumma and haenyeo, coming back from the sea. Haenyeo are famous for being the heads of the household, bringing in money for the family while men take care of the children, letting Jeju develop a matriarchal society. You can also find these powerful and indipendent divers in the UNESCO‚Äôs Intangible Cultural Heritage list. Feel empowered yet?

Hey, 2018.
I kinda ranted about you on Facebook already but here on Instagram I want to highlight the beauty you showed me in these months.

I don‚Äôt even remember how was my life before coming to Japan, it was just work, work, singing, work, work and work (and singing).
But since I‚Äôm here I can‚Äôt say that it changed that much lol now it‚Äôs even worse, cause it became just school, work, school, work, work and school.
For poor people like me being able to do the tourist life in the country you‚Äôre living in it‚Äôs kinda impossible (especially if it‚Äôs Japan lol), and that‚Äôs the saddest thing ever. But this doesn‚Äôt mean that I didn‚Äôt take the chance to make the best out of Tokyo.

So, what did I achieve this year?

This year marks a lot of ‚Äúfirsts‚Äù:
First long adventure far away from home.
First proper concerts, held by my two favorite groups atm.
First (and hopefully not last) holiday trip to South Korea with the best partner I could have asked for.
First proper hangover with puke and everything.
First lebanese experience (lol) and ok let‚Äôs say lots of other first things that happened here in Tokyo that I don‚Äôt want to write down lmao

And I‚Äôve worked hard.
I‚Äôm still working hard.
I won‚Äôt be the very best like no one ever was, but I‚Äôll always try to do my very best at least.
All the gratifications and satisfactions that Tokyo brought me will always be my strength to keep going.
So come at me, 2019.
Try me, bitch.
I‚Äôm ready. (Don‚Äôt hit me too hard tho, pls). #newyear #newyearseve #tokyo #japan #friends #goodmemories #goodvibes #achievement #resolution #bye2018 #welcome2019 #partying #thankyou

I want to tell you a story.
Two years ago I bought this pretty Japanese kids‚Äô book in one of the most beautiful book shops in Italy, during one of the most beautiful holiday I‚Äôve ever spent, in Venice.
I wasn‚Äôt that sure to buy it cause I didn‚Äôt know if I could ever read it, but today I‚Äôm glad I did. Better late than never, right?

This is the story of a grandpa who lives alone in the middle of the sea in a house built over several blocks, like the children‚Äôs toy ones. As the sea level raises, the water would flood the house and the grandpa would build another house on top of it. His wife dies 3 years earlier but he continues to live in their house, cooking with her apron, playing chess with a neighbor, reading his sons‚Äô letters and sleeping at night with the sea waves‚Äô sound to cradle him. On a winter‚Äôs day, the water reaches again grandpa‚Äôs house floor and he decides to build a new house. Accidentally, he drops the tools in the fishing puddle and decides to get them back diving in the seawater. As he goes down, he clearly recalls all the events that took place there with granny, living together in their previous houses: when on her deathbed he wouldn‚Äôt let her hands away from his grip, when the parade would come in town and bring joy to their grandchildren, when they raised their first grandchild building swings and sewing clothes for her, watched their eldest daughter getting married and found their lost cat among the neighbors‚Äô ships. The more he dives the more he remembers their very first little house, just the two of them, with no water around, but just land, grass and trees as a frame of it. He definitely wouldn‚Äôt leave that house ever.
The spring comes, the new house is completed and grandpa smiles widely looking at a dandelion bloomed through the wall‚Äôs cracks of his tiny house. 
Now, you can imagine my big fat ass crying through the tale, cause it was like reading an alternative UP! story, and I hope they really don‚Äôt let the kids read this cause what the hell, it‚Äôs sad as fuck, but it was so emotional and I thank myself for taking this book in my hand again and read it for the first time after two years of getting dusty on my shelf.
